76561197963161776,Recommended,270270,29340403,Posted: 18 January,all,Razor,"Really interesting game so far!Something to know is that the game world is made of individual areas that are randomly scattered on a large world map. You simply fast-travel between areas on the world map, but once you reach an area you can explore it with your character. It's similar to games like Fallout 2 or Dead State.Combat is in real time, hack-and-slash style, but it's supposed to be a last resort. As far as I can tell, using stealth to avoid enemies is far more viable. Fighting only gets you hurt and makes you waste supplies, although you can find helpful loot on enemies.+ The scavenging aspect of the game is really interesting. You'll have to thoroughly explore various locations to find stuff you need. The different locations are very nice and well-detailed, and quite large too. No two areas feel the same, and every element of the map has it's place and a purpose. There's also some hidden areas that you won't notice unless you pay attention when you explore.Searchable containers can only be highlighted with your mouse when you are very close to them, so you'll need to really search around for stuff and you won't immediately see everything that is searchable at a glance as soon as you enter a room. There's also a lot of locked doors that you can open in different ways, which adds some obstacles to your exploration and keeps you active.You'll also need to avoid the mutants as much as you can, which adds challenge to your scavenging. You can't just kill all the enemies in a building and then search it peacefully, you'll have to use stealth and be careful not to get caught.Finally, you'll need to plan your scavenging runs carefully. Make sure you pack enough gear with you, but don't take too much either or you won't be able to bring a lot of stuff back with you. You have to consider how far you are going, what you want to bring back with you, and what supplies you will be able to find or craft at your destination. If you're exploring a forest, you probably don't need to bring a lot of firewood and food with you.+ Crafting is important. You can find a lot of stuff by scavenging, but you won't always get everything you need. To acquire the stuff that scavenging doesn't give you, you need to craft and cook. A handmade axe, bandages, clean water... Crafting isn't just an option in this game. When you get back to your camp after exploring another area, you need to start crafting the stuff that you need before you go out again.+ The mutants are cool. They're creepy (as well as their names) and there's a bunch of different types. The models are also well detailed if you look closely, they have all sorts of unsettling physical attributes. They really make you wonder what exactly could have caused them to look that way. They really make you curious about the backstory, and I hope the game reveals lots of information about the mutation.+ The survival aspect of the game is well developed. You have to watch your body temperature, your hunger and thirst, and various health attributes (poison, bleeding, burns, fractures...). You have to craft items to keep you alive and you even have to clean your water or make sure your food isn't contaminated. If you're a beginner don't worry, on normal difficulty the survival aspect is not too hard to manage. But it is a survival game, so you need to pay attention to these things and you can't simply ignore them.+ If you die on normal difficulty, you can restart from the beginning of the area so you won't lose all your progress. To keep things challenging, the area also resets: monsters, searchable containers and items all change. There's permanent death on harder difficulties.+ You develop your character's skills by finding a special medication. It's an interesting mechanic, you find the drug randomly by exploring or looting enemies. So obviously the more you fight or explore, the more likely you are to find that drug, but there's still a randomness element to it.+ There are vehicles to help you move around and carry more things. They need fuel though.+ Hunting wild animals is an option for surviving, but you probably can't survive solely on this. It's a good way to find food and animal pelts to craft clothing with.+ Can't say I've noticed any bugs. There are probably a few, but so far I haven't seen any. The devs must really have worked hard to clean them.- The movement mechanic takes some getting used to. Your character seems slow to respond sometimes. It can be frustrating in the begnning if you try playing this game like a hack-and-slash, but it's fine once you realize that this isn't how the game is meant to be played. You're supposed to move stealthily, and melee fighting should only be a last resort. Also you're supposed to be really cold most of the time, and in real life that does make your reaction time slower.If your character had the reflexes of a ninja, combat would be far too easy and you would just slaughter monsters with no trouble. So the movement mechanic is not so bad, you have to get used to it and it can be a bit annoying at first, but after a few hours it's not really noticeable and overall it helps the game.Overall, I'd recommend this game to anyone who enjoys survival or scavenging games with horror elements. I'm actually surprised it isn't more popular, because despite minor flaws it has a lot going for it. Make sure you give it a few hours to convince you!"
76561198053292615,Recommended,270270,11047403,"Posted: 3 July, 2014",all,10k,"For those of you that want a video First Impressions, here you go :-http://youtu.be/nQ1bZ3dsPMwPleasently surprised by this game. While the survival genre isn't exactly new (and let's face it, survival as a genre is very over-saturated these days) this game brings a rather unique twist with it being based very cold temperatures that make exploration need very careful planning, as one wrong decision can cost you dearly, either from freezing to death or the alien hybrids that have nothing better to do than to make your life a misery.Interiors of buildings are randomly generated which in turn mean that items are also randomly generated. Your starting gear is also randomly generated to an extent too, which is rather nice as it brings a fair bit of variety. A decent example is that the first time I played I got a nice revolver with plenty of ammo. The second time round I didn't get a revolver and the third time I got a revolver but had the wrong ammo type.The hybrids hurt, It is advised to try and avoid combat if possible (however you could go in guns/axes ablazing, just don't expect to be in one piece after though :p). You can sneak by crouching or walking to reduce noise you make, as far as I can tell it seems to work well enough.While the controls can get a bit of getting used to, they work fairly well. Line of Sight is implemented very well in this game where you have a cone of sight that is movable with the mouse.Really enjoying it so far, although I haven't put in as much time as I would like. Would love to see more crafting options, randomly generated maps (as well as interiors) and more functionality. I will be following the game to see how the devs expand the game."
